# üêû Bug report

I'm still struggeling with the webpack  related warnings: `Module parse failed: Unexpected token (8:28) You may need an appropriate loader to handle this file type`.  during ng serve after updating to Angular 8. The referred solutions of [#14566] (https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/issues/14566) didn't work for us. 


### Command
```
- [ ] new
- [ ] build
- [x ] serve
- [ ] test
- [ ] e2e
- [ ] generate
- [ ] add
- [ ] update
- [ ] lint
- [ ] xi18n
- [ ] run
- [ ] config
- [ ] help
- [ ] version
- [ ] doc
```

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction
Updating a solution that uses dynamic import() during runtime to angular 8.

## üî¨ More detailed explanation:
I'm using the `NgModuleFactory` to dynamically create a `ModuleFactory` which finally will be used to create a `ComponentFactory` to create a component of a specific not yet loaded module. Therefore I'm using the `import` function and the returning promise to create the needed ComponentFactory using the `compileModuleAsync` function.
<pre><code>
` import('../../admin/admin.module').then(result => {
          this.compiler.compileModuleAsync(AdminModule).then(moduleFactory => {
           // Handle modulefactory
          });
</code></pre>

**The warning is thrown for each component of the loaded module.**


## üî• Exception or Error
```
You may need an appropriate loader to handle this file type, currently no loaders are configured to process this file. See https://webpack.js.org/concepts#loaders
| 
> <my-component>
| </my-component>

```


