### Is this a regression?
No, this behavior was not there in versions previous to angular 8.0

### Description
Differential loading is an awesome feature. Thanks for that!

I have some problems creating a nice developer workflow, with nice I mean serving es5 compliant code (also for testing). I know about the option creating a special tsconfig-es5.app.json for that purpose and then run with `ng serve --configuration es5`. But this does not solve my problem involving a library (also included in the git repo)

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction
I created a GitHub repository, where the code for the following two approaches lives.

**First Approach**
checkout https://github.com/shiftcode/ng-issue-investigation/tree/%231-es2015-build-only

```
npm i
npx ng build
```


The typescript library delivers a single artifact with `tsconfig.target = es2015`. When running `npx ng build` everything works as expected. The es2015 class construct will be transpiled to function, so legacy (es5) browsers are supported (yes IE11, looking at you).


```
// vendor-es5.js
/***/ "./node_modules/@sample/ts-library/dist/_es2015/messenger.js":
/*!*******************************************************************!*\
  !*** ./node_modules/@sample/ts-library/dist/_es2015/messenger.js ***!
  \*******************************************************************/
/*! exports provided: Messenger */
/***/ (function (module, __webpack_exports__, __webpack_require__) {
  "use strict";
  __webpack_require__.r(__webpack_exports__);
  /* harmony export (binding) */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, "Messenger", function () { return Messenger; });
  var Messenger = /** @class */ (function () {
    function Messenger() {
    }
    Messenger.prototype.talk = function () {
      return 'i am just talking';
    };
    return Messenger;
  }());
  //# sourceMappingURL=messenger.js.map
  /***/
})
```

when running `ng serve --configuration es5` IE11 will fail with syntax error, because es2015 class is not transpiled by webpack.

``` 
// vendor.js
/***/ "./node_modules/@sample/ts-library/dist/_es2015/messenger.js":
/*!*******************************************************************!*\
  !*** ./node_modules/@sample/ts-library/dist/_es2015/messenger.js ***!
  \*******************************************************************/
/*! exports provided: Messenger */
/***/ (function(module, __webpack_exports__, __webpack_require__) {

"use strict";
__webpack_require__.r(__webpack_exports__);
/* harmony export (binding) */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, "Messenger", function() { return Messenger; });
class Messenger {
    talk() {
        return 'i am just talking';
    }
}
//# sourceMappingURL=messenger.js.map
```

so this approach does not work.

**Second Approach**
checkout https://github.com/shiftcode/ng-issue-investigation/tree/%232-multi-platform-lib-build

Run the following in ng-client:
```
npm i 
npx ng serve --configuration es5
```

The library now provides different entry points, check [package.json](https://github.com/shiftcode/ng-issue-investigation/blob/%232-multi-platform-lib-build/ts-library/package.json) . This is actually the preferred approach, because then we could also use esNext features, because we have a separate build (`tsc --target es5`) transpiling unsupported features.

When running `npx ng serve --configuration es5` everything works as expected in IE11. In comparison running `npx ng build` will not load the correct file for es5 build, instead it loads from `ts-library/dist/_es2015`. (check vendor-es5.js and you will see the string _i am just talking es2015_ instead of _i am just talking es5_).

So for me the question remains about how differential loading supports IE11 with live reloading. Hopefully you can also shed some light in why the files are not loaded / or transpiled as expected.

Thanks in advance for any help!

